{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17620321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17620321"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:40:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:40:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16617"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16617"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0.04,0,0.06,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9308"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66950"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9308","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9308"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16617"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52404"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5016"},{"type":"tags","id":"9833"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22066"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22387"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66950"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset right-sided weakness and slurred speech. Her symptoms began 2 hours ago. Computed tomography shows no evidence of haemorrhage. After confirming eligibility criteria, the medical team decides to administer alteplase for acute ischaemic stroke.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of alteplase?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Converts plasminogen to plasmin","Inhibits platelet aggregation","Blocks vitamin K synthesis","Inhibits thrombin formation","Directly breaks down fibrin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETissue plasminogen activator (tPA) \u003Cstrong\u003Econverts plasminogen to plasmin\u003C/strong\u003E, which then breaks down fibrin in blood clots. tPA has high specificity for fibrin-bound plasminogen, making it an effective targeted therapy for dissolving existing clots.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits platelet aggregation\u003C/strong\u003E: is the mechanism of anti-platelet medications like aspirin, clopidogrel and glycoprotein IIb/IIIa inhibitors. These drugs prevent new clot formation but do not break down existing clots.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks vitamin K synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E: this describes warfarin\u0027s mechanism, which prevents the formation of clotting factors II, VII, IX and X. This is not useful in acute situations as it takes days to achieve effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits thrombin formation\u003C/strong\u003E: this option describes anticoagulants like heparin and direct thrombin inhibitors which prevent new clot formation but do not dissolve existing clots.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly breaks down fibrin\u003C/strong\u003E: while fibrin breakdown is the end result, tPA works indirectly by first activating plasmin, which is the enzyme that actually degrades fibrin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EtPA is used clinically in situations requiring rapid clot dissolution, such as acute ischaemic stroke (within 4.5 hours) and myocardial infarction, where it helps restore blood flow to affected tissues.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tissue plasminogen activator (tPA) converts plasminogen to plasmin, which breaks down fibrin clots.","tPA is highly specific for fibrin-bound plasminogen, making it effective for targeted clot dissolution.","tPA is used clinically for treating acute ischaemic stroke and myocardial infarction within specific time windows."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52404"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16617"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52404"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-03T08:34:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T08:35:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9308"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66950"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"rel